'''Allahdino''' is a small village belonging to the [[Indus Valley Civilisation|Harappan]] period, located 40&nbsp;km east of [[Karachi]]. It is an unfortified settlement of 1.4 hectare, established in a coastal area of [[Pakistan]].<ref name=Singh>{{cite book|last=Singh|first=Upinder|title=A History of Ancient and Early Medieval India: From the Stone Age to the 12th Century|year=2008|publisher=Pearson Education India|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-813-17-1120-0|page=156|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H3lUIIYxWkEC&pg |accessdate=30 June 2012}}</ref> This small but well organised settlement was abandoned by c.2000 BC.<ref name=McIntosh>{{cite book|last=McIntosh|first=Jane|title=The Ancient Indus Civilisation: New Perspectives|year=2008|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, California|isbn=9781576079072|pages=93,229,333,327|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1AJO2A-CbccC&printsec=frontcover&dq=the+ancient+indus+valley&hl=en&sa=X&ei=wd3vT-esGImGrAfPyPm9DQ&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=allahdino&f=false}}</ref>
==Excavations== Several mud brick houses, sometimes built on stone platforms were excavated from this site. A large multiroomed house with a mudbrick platform was also excavated. One building had three wells, with diameters of 60&nbsp;cm to 90&nbsp;cm. In fact, all the wells found on this site had similarly small diameters.<ref name="Singh"/> The layout of the settlement and buildings suggest that Allahdino was involved with administrative role.<ref name=McIntosh229>{{cite book|last=McIntosh|first=Jane|title=The Ancient Indus Civilisation: New Perspectives|year=2008|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, California|isbn=9781576079072|pages=229|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1AJO2A-CbccC&printsec=frontcover&dq=the+ancient+indus+valley&hl=en&sa=X&ei=wd3vT-esGImGrAfPyPm9DQ&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=allahdino&f=false}}</ref>
==Artifacts found== Large quantities of [[copper]] objects, triangular terracotta cakes, seals, small [[terracotta]] jars with profusions of [[gold]], [[silver]], [[bronze]] and other ornaments were found.<ref name=Singh/> Several jars, one containing gold and silver ornaments, were also found here.<ref name=McIntosh333>{{cite book|last=McIntosh|first=Jane|title=The Ancient Indus Civilisation: New Perspectives|year=2008|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, California|isbn=9781576079072|pages=333|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1AJO2A-CbccC&printsec=frontcover&dq=the+ancient+indus+valley&hl=en&sa=X&ei=wd3vT-esGImGrAfPyPm9DQ&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=allahdino&f=false}}</ref> A belt containing 36 [[carnelian]] beads was found, proof of highly skilled workers being settled in the area.<ref name=McIntosh327>{{cite book|last=McIntosh|first=Jane|title=The Ancient Indus Civilisation: New Perspectives|year=2008|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, California|isbn=9781576079072|pages=327|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1AJO2A-CbccC&printsec=frontcover&dq=the+ancient+indus+valley&hl=en&sa=X&ei=wd3vT-esGImGrAfPyPm9DQ&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=allahdino&f=false}}</ref> [[Archeologists]] believe that findings of gold and silver ornaments, as well as the usage of stone at the village indicate some of the residents were well to do.<ref name=Singh/> This site is well excavated one and a total of 240,000 vessels and shreds were collected and tabulated.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dales,|first=George F.|last2=Kenoyer|first2=Jonathan M.|title=Excavations at Mohenjo Daro, Pakistan : the pottery, with an account of the pottery from the 1950 excavations of Sir Mortimer Wheeler|year=1986|publisher=University Museum, University of Pennsylvania|location=Philadelphia|isbn=9780934718523|pages=9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4iew_THp8foC&printsec=frontcover&dq=kenoyer&hl=en&sa=X&ei=gIb1T6z8IcfhrAeyu6XVBg&ved=0CEAQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=kenoyer&f=false|last3=Alcock |first3=Leslie}}</ref>
==Importance== Water from the wells of Allahdino would have been used to irrigate nearby fields.<ref name=Singh/> Allahdino is also thought to have been associated with textile manufacturing.<ref name=McIntosh333/>
