[[File:Welcome City Hall Detroit.jpg|thumb|The [[Detroit City Hall]] in 1900. It was razed in 1961.]]
The '''Detroit Century Box''' is a [[time capsule]] that was created in the U.S. city of [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]] on December 31, 1900. Mayor [[William C. Maybury]] organized the capsule which consists of a copper box filled with photos and letters containing the then current state of affairs in Detroit along with predictions for the future. Mayor [[Dennis Archer]] presided over the opening of the capsule on December 31, 2000.<ref>Andrea Cecil, [http://www.mlive.com/living/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2008/12/oncall_request_time_capsule.html "100-year-old time capsule opened in Detroit"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130619062052/http://www.mlive.com/living/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2008/12/oncall_request_time_capsule.html |date=2013-06-19 }} Republished from the ''[[Kalamazoo Gazette]]'' (January 2, 2001). Retrieved August 13, 2013</ref><ref>[http://detroithistorical.wordpress.com/2012/10/12/future-friday-century-box-prophecies/ "Future Friday: Century Box Prophecies"] Detroit Historical Society. Retrieved August 13, 2013</ref>
==Detroit in 1900== {{Quote|text= Our buildings of today are equipped with fast running elevators, heating, lighting, power plants... |sign= John M. Donaldson |source= Rise of Architecture in Detroit<ref name="Donaldson" />}} {{Quote|text= In the diocese there 218 priests - 44 Regulars - 174 Seculars. 198 Churches and missions... |sign= John Samuel Foley |source= Letter to William C. Maybury<ref name="Foley" />}} {{Quote|text= We travel by railroad and with steam power from Detroit to Chicago in less than eight hours... |sign= William C. Maybury |source= Letter of William C. Maybury<ref name="Maybury" />}} {{Quote|text= Of the 44 United States, 25 have limited suffrage, 4 have full suffrage, limited suffrage is granted in many foreign countries and full suffrage in New Zealand, South and West Australia, and in Isle of Man. |sign= Sara M. Philleo Skinner |source= Woman's Suffrage - Retrospect and Prophecy<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://detroiths.pastperfect-online.com/33029cgi/mweb.exe?request=record;id=E557B87F-4165-4843-9D17-886740941913;type=301 |title= Woman's Suffrage - Retrospect and Prophecy |publisher= Detroit Historical Society}}</ref>}}
==Predictions for the future== {{Quote|text= In AD 2000, I think it not improbable that Detroit will enjoy a population of fully four millions. |sign= James E. Scripps |source= Letter to William C. Maybury<ref name="Scripps" />}} {{Quote|text= I predict further that Sandwich, Windsor and Walkerville now in Canada will be a part of the City of Detroit and that Ontario will be a state of the United States of America. |sign= Orrin R. Baldwin |source= Letter to William C. Maybury<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://detroiths.pastperfect-online.com/33029cgi/mweb.exe?request=record;id=71856A78-F264-4EA9-9AE9-635931413703;type=301 |title= Letter written by Orrin R. Baldwin |publisher= Detroit Historical Society}}</ref>}} {{Quote|text= That prisoners instead of being conveyed to the several police stations in Automobile patrol wagons will be sent through pneumatic tubes, flying machines, or some similar process. |sign= Commissioners of the Metropolitan Police Commission |source= Letter to William C. Maybury<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://detroiths.pastperfect-online.com/33029cgi/mweb.exe?request=record;id=80ACD1B3-2F8B-4BF8-AA08-756855300000;type=301 |title= Metropolitan Police Commission |publisher= Detroit Historical Society}}</ref>}}
